## âš™ï¸ **4. Azure Resources and Resource Groups**

| Concept                 | Description                                                                                                                                 | Example                                                    |
| ----------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Resource**            | Basic unit you create or use in Azure.                                                                                                      | VM, Database, Function App.                                |
| **Resource Group (RG)** | Logical container for related resources.                                                                                                    | Group all resources for one app (e.g., website) in one RG. |
| **Key Rules**           | 1ï¸âƒ£ One resource belongs to **one RG** only.<br>2ï¸âƒ£ RGs **canâ€™t be nested**.<br>3ï¸âƒ£ Actions (delete, access) apply to all resources inside. | Deleting â€œWebApp-RGâ€ deletes all its resources.            |

### ğŸ’¡ Example

If you create a **temporary Dev environment**, place all its resources in one RG â†’ when done, **delete the RG** to remove everything at once.

---

## ğŸ’³ **5. Azure Subscriptions**

| Aspect                  | Description                                                                                                      | Example                                                                      |
| ----------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Purpose**             | Container that defines **billing, access control, and quotas**.                                                  | â€œFinance Department Subscriptionâ€.                                           |
| **Relationship**        | A single account can have **multiple subscriptions**.                                                            | One for Dev, one for Production.                                             |
| **Types of Boundaries** | - **Billing boundary:** Controls how charges are grouped.<br>- **Access boundary:** Defines who can access what. | Separate subscription for each team or project.                              |
| **Links To**            | An **Azure account** (identity in Microsoft Entra ID).                                                           | User: [sai@contoso.com](mailto:sai@contoso.com) linked to two subscriptions. |

### ğŸ“˜ Example:

* **Sub 1 (Dev)** â€“ Lower-cost VMs, developers have full access.
* **Sub 2 (Prod)** â€“ Strict access, monitored billing.

---

## ğŸ—‚ï¸ **6. When to Create Additional Subscriptions**

| Reason                       | Use Case                             | Example                                                   |
| ---------------------------- | ------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Environment Separation**   | Separate Dev/Test/Prod environments. | Avoid accidental changes in Production.                   |
| **Organizational Structure** | Divide per team or department.       | HR, Finance, Marketing.                                   |
| **Billing Management**       | Separate billing and cost tracking.  | Production subscription for client apps, another for R&D. |

---

## ğŸ¢ **7. Azure Management Groups**

| Concept              | Description                                                                                                        | Example                                                                                |
| -------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Management Group** | Top-level container above subscriptions. Used to apply policies and access controls across multiple subscriptions. | â€œGlobal IT Policy Groupâ€.                                                              |
| **Purpose**          | Centralized governance, policy enforcement, and access management for large enterprises.                           | Limit VM regions or apply security policies to all child subscriptions.                |
| **Inheritance**      | Subscriptions under a management group **automatically inherit** its policies and permissions.                     | If policy â€œVMs only in USâ€ is applied at MG level â†’ all child subscriptions follow it. |
| **Structure**        | Can be **nested** (up to 6 levels deep).                                                                           | Root â†’ Continent â†’ Country â†’ Department.                                               |

